T}@T{
T}
T{
\f[CR]RGBA32I\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]RGBA_INTEGER\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]INT\f[R]
T}@T{
(R, G, B, A) = (i32, i32, i32, i32)
T}@T{
Y
T}@T{
T}
.TE
.PP
In WebGL 2, when specifying the source as \f[CR]srcData\f[R] or
\f[CR]offset\f[R], the following combinations are additionally
available, and they can be enabled in WebGL 1 via the
\f[CR]WEBGL_depth_texture\f[R] extension:
.PP
.TS
tab(@);
lw(12.8n) lw(10.9n) lw(32.8n) lw(13.5n).
T{
\f[CR]internalformat\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]format\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]type\f[R]
T}@T{
Internal pixel layout
T}
_
T{
\f[CR]DEPTH_COMPONENT16\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]DEPTH_COMPONENT\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_SHORT\f[R], \f[CR]UNSIGNED_INT\f[R]
T}@T{
(D) = (16)
T}
T{
\f[CR]DEPTH_COMPONENT24\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]DEPTH_COMPONENT\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_INT\f[R]
T}@T{
(D) = (24)
T}
T{
\f[CR]DEPTH_COMPONENT32F\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]DEPTH_COMPONENT\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]FLOAT\f[R]
T}@T{
(D) = (f32)
T}
T{
\f[CR]DEPTH24_STENCIL8\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]DEPTH_STENCIL\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_INT_24_8\f[R] (\f[CR]ext.UNSIGNED_INT_24_8_WEBGL\f[R])
T}@T{
(D, S) = (24, 8)
T}
T{
\f[CR]DEPTH32F_STENCIL8\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]DEPTH_STENCIL\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]FLOAT_32_UNSIGNED_INT_24_8_REV\f[R]
T}@T{
(D, S) = (f32, 8)
T}
.TE
.PP
When the data source is a DOM pixel source, commonly each channel\(cqs
representation is an unsigned integer type of at least 8 bits.
Converting such representation to signed integers or unsigned integers
with more bits is not clearly defined.
For example, when converting \f[CR]RGBA8\f[R] to \f[CR]RGBA16UI\f[R], it
is unclear whether or not the intention is to scale up values to the
full range of a 16\-bit unsigned integer.
Therefore, only converting to unsigned integer of at most 8 bits, half
float, or float is allowed.
.RE
.PP
The texture source can be provided in one of three ways: from an
\f[CR]ArrayBuffer\f[R] (possibly shared) using \f[CR]srcData\f[R] and
\f[CR]srcOffset\f[R]; from a DOM pixel \f[CR]source\f[R]; or, in WebGL
2, from \f[CR]gl.PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\f[R] using \f[CR]offset\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]srcData\f[R]
A \f[CR]TypedArray\f[R] or \f[CR]DataView\f[R] containing the compressed
texture data.
Its type must match the \f[CR]type\f[R] parameter:
.RS
.PP
.TS
tab(@);
lw(21.8n) lw(48.2n).
T{
\f[CR]srcData\f[R] type
T}@T{
\f[CR]type\f[R] value
T}
_
T{
\f[CR]Int8Array\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]BYTE\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]Uint8Array\f[R], \f[CR]Uint8ClampedArray\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_BYTE\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]Int16Array\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]SHORT\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]Uint16Array\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_SHORT\f[R], \f[CR]UNSIGNED_SHORT_5_6_5\f[R],
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_SHORT_5_5_5_1\f[R], \f[CR]UNSIGNED_SHORT_4_4_4_4\f[R],
\f[CR]HALF_FLOAT\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]Int32Array\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]INT\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]Uint32Array\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_INT\f[R], \f[CR]UNSIGNED_INT_5_9_9_9_REV\f[R],
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_INT_2_10_10_10_REV\f[R],
\f[CR]UNSIGNED_INT_10F_11F_11F_REV\f[R], \f[CR]UNSIGNED_INT_24_8\f[R]
T}
T{
\f[CR]Float32Array\f[R]
T}@T{
\f[CR]FLOAT\f[R]
T}
.TE
.PP
When \f[CR]type\f[R] is \f[CR]FLOAT_32_UNSIGNED_INT_24_8_REV\f[R],
\f[CR]srcData\f[R] must be \f[CR]null\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]srcOffset\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
(WebGL 2 only) An integer specifying the index of \f[CR]srcData\f[R] to
start reading from.
Defaults to \f[CR]0\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]source\f[R]
Read from a DOM pixel source, which can be one of:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]ImageBitmap\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]ImageData\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]HTMLImageElement\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]HTMLCanvasElement\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]HTMLVideoElement\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]OffscreenCanvas\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]VideoFrame\f[R]
In WebGL 1, the \f[CR]width\f[R] and \f[CR]height\f[R] are always
inferred from the source.
In WebGL 2, they can also be explicitly specified.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]offset\f[R]
(WebGL 2 only) A \f[CR]GLintptr\f[R] specifying the starting address in
the buffer bound to \f[CR]gl.PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\f[R].
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
gl.texImage2D(gl.TEXTURE_2D, 0, gl.RGBA, gl.RGBA, gl.UNSIGNED_BYTE, image);
.EE
